---
import "../styles/global.css";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
---

<!doctype html>

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />

    <meta
      name="viewport"
      content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"
    />

    <title>
      The Problem of Tolerance | Minimal Tolerance
    </title>

    <meta
      name="description"
      content="The moral and economic foundations of the Theory of Minimal Tolerance"
    />

    <link
      rel="canonical"
      href="https://minimaltolerance.com/theory/"
    />
  </head>

  <body>
    <Header />

    <main>

      <!-- PAGE TITLE -->

      <section class="page-hero">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE THEORY
          </p>

          <h1>
            The problem of tolerance
          </h1>
        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- OPENING STATEMENT -->

      <section class="statement">

        <blockquote>
          The State does not become legitimate.
          At most, it may be tolerated
        </blockquote>

      </section>

      <!-- MORAL PROBLEM -->

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE MORAL PROBLEM
          </p>

          <h2>
            Political authority rests on coercion
          </h2>

        <p>
        The State is routinely exempted from principles that 
        govern every other human relationship. Consent is treated 
        as essential in private interactions but becomes secondary
        once political authority enters the picture
        </p>

        <p>
        The relationship between the individual and the State is 
        neither voluntary nor optional. Disagreement does not 
        eliminate the obligation to comply, nor does it release 
        individuals from rules imposed without their personal agreement
        </p>

        <p>
        The ability to impose a decision does not establish a 
        right to impose it. Coercion may secure compliance, but 
        compliance and legitimacy are not the same thing
        </p>
        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- EFFICIENCY PROBLEM -->

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

         <p class="eyebrow">
  THE EFFICIENCY PROBLEM
</p>

<h2>
  Why centralized decisions fail
</h2>

<p>
  The knowledge required to coordinate a complex society
  is dispersed among millions of individuals. No planner
  can know what millions of people know about their own
  circumstances
</p>

<p>
  Prices communicate information about scarcity,
  preferences and opportunity costs. They allow
  individuals to coordinate their decisions without
  requiring a central authority to direct the process
</p>

<p>
  The State replaces decentralized choices with political
  direction while operating with less information, weaker
  feedback and fewer mechanisms for correcting error
</p>
        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- MARKET FAILURE -->

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

      <p class="eyebrow">
  MARKET FAILURE
</p>

<h2>
  The existence of a problem does not establish the case for coercion
</h2>

<p>
  Imperfect outcomes are often treated as automatic
  justification for state action. The diagnosis quickly
  becomes a prescription, as though identifying a
  difficulty were enough to validate the proposed remedy
</p>

<p>
  The comparison is rarely symmetrical. Markets are
  judged as they exist, while governments are often
  evaluated as they are imagined. Real institutions face
  the same limits of knowledge, incentives and
  coordination
</p>

<p>
  Difficulties do not disappear when decisions are moved
  into political hands. They change form, shift location
  or become harder to observe
</p>

        </div>

      </section>

   
      <!-- STRUCTURAL FREE RIDER -->

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

        

         <p class="eyebrow">
  NOT A MARKET FAILURE
</p>

<h2>
  A structural free-rider problem
</h2>

<p>
  The phenomenon addressed here is not a market failure
  in the classical sense. Labeling it as such creates
  confusion and obscures the nature of the problem
</p>

<p>
  Individuals may receive a benefit regardless of whether
  they contribute to its provision. When exclusion is
  difficult or impossible, the incentive to withhold
  payment grows
</p>

<p>
  The relevant case is narrower: situations in which
  voluntary provision collapses persistently because of
  the incentive structure itself. The objection is not
  moral, but operational
</p>


        </div>

      </section>

 <!-- LINK TO THEOREM -->

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">

            THE THEOREM
          </p>

          <h2>
            Defining the boundary
          </h2>

                <div class="buttons">

            <a href="/theorem/" class="primary">
              Read the Theorem
            </a>

          </div>



        </div>

      </section> 


     
    </main>

    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
